SIMPLE: fellowship
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fellowship
<hw>Fel"low*ship</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Fellow +
-ship.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or relation of being or
associate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Companionship of persons on equal and friendly
terms; frequent and familiar intercourse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In a great town, friends are scattered, so that there is not that
<qex>fellowship</qex> which is in less neighborhods.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men are made for society and mutual <qex>fellowship</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Calamy.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A state of being together; companionship;
partnership; association; hence, confederation; joint
interest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The great contention of the sea and skies⟦br⟧
Parted our <qex>fellowship</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fellowship</qex> in pain divides not smart</q>.
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fellowship</qex> in woe doth woe assuage</q>.
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The goodliest <qex>fellowship</qex> of famous knights,⟦br⟧
Whereof this world holds record.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Those associated with one, as in a family, or a
society; a company.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sorrow of Noah with his <qex>fellowship</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With that a joyous <qex>fellowship</qex> issued⟦br⟧
Of minstrels.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Eng. & Amer. Universities)</fld> <def>A foundation
for the maintenance, on certain conditions, of a scholar called a
fellow, who usually resides at the university.</def> <-- why
"foundation"? stipend is more accurate now. This use is sense 4 of this
dictionary, an "endowment" -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Arith.)</fld> <def>The rule for dividing profit and
loss among partners; -- called also partnership, company, and
distributive proportion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>Good fellowship</b></col>, <cd>companionableness; the
spirit and disposition befitting comrades.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There's neither honesty, manhood, nor good <qex>fellowship</qex>
in thee.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><-- p. 551 --></p>

<p><ent>Fellowship</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fellowship
<hw>Fel"low*ship</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Fellowshiped</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos>. <conjf>Fellowshiping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld>
<def>To acknowledge as of good standing, or in communion according to
standards of faith and practice; to admit to Christian
fellowship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Felly</ent>⟦br⟧
